※※
# scaffold-sky-workflow

Manually-run meta-workflow that authors a brand-new `.sky` workflow from a
plain-English brief, then lints it until it passes. Flow:

  (manual run: --var dir, name, request)
       │
       ▼
   ┌────────┐   writes from {{request}}   ┌──────────────────┐
   │ author │ ──────────────────────────▶ │ <dir>/<name>/workflow.sky │
   └────────┘   (sky-workflow-authoring)  └──────────────────┘
       │                                          ▲
       ▼                                          │ edits to fix errors
   ┌────────┐                                     │
   │  lint  │ ─── sky lint ──▶ errors? ──yes──▶ fix┘   (loop, max 6 passes)
   └────────┘                     │
                                  no (clean)
                                   │
                                   ▼
                                 done

Run it (you choose where the file lands with --var dir):

  sky run scaffold-sky-workflow \
    --var dir=".sky/workflows" \
    --var name="deploy-on-tag" \
    --var request="on a GitHub release, run the deploy script and post the result to Slack"

  - dir     directory the file is written to — STATE THIS before running (e.g. .sky/workflows)
  - name    kebab-case directory name (generates <dir>/<name>/workflow.sky)
  - request what the workflow should do, in plain English

Language: the brief in {{request}} may be in any language. The generated
workflow is always written in English (name, keys, node ids, prompt bodies);
only the ※※ comment blocks may be in the brief's language.

Required skill — install before first run (no marketplace plugin needed):

  sky library install sky-workflow-authoring
※※

⊕meta⊕
name = "scaffold-sky-workflow"
description = "Author a new .sky workflow from a plain-English brief and lint it until clean. Fire via: sky run scaffold-sky-workflow --var dir=<dir> --var name=<file> --var request=<what it should do>"
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 2.00
ui = "ui/workflow"
⊕⊕

※author※
Step 1 — author. Writes the new workflow file from the brief ({{request}}) via the
sky-workflow-authoring skill. Outputs {{dir}}/{{name}}/workflow.sky. No edges.
※※

§author§
model = "sonnet"
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
ui = "ui/author"
§§

∆author∆
Author a new Skylence `.sky` workflow at {{dir}}/{{name}}/workflow.sky.

What it must do: {{request}}

Language rule: the brief above may be written in any language. Write the workflow itself entirely in English — `name`, all config keys, node ids, and every ∆ prompt body. Only the ※※ comment blocks may be written in the brief's language, to document the workflow for its author.

Follow the sky-workflow-authoring skill exactly: the four Unicode delimiter blocks (⊕meta⊕, §id§, ∆id∆, ※※), `name = "{{name}}"` matching the filename, exactly one trigger, and a sensible node DAG. Pick node types (claude / bash / script / http / loop) that fit the brief. Two audiences (per the skill): write the ∆ prompt bodies for the model (terse, machine-oriented, no concern for human readability); write the ※※ comment blocks for the human (clear, and when the flow branches/loops/gates add the diagram that explains it fastest: ASCII, Mermaid, sequence, or swimlane). Create the {{dir}} directory if absent.

File editing rule: if `skylence_read` and `skylence_edit` MCP tools are available (sky MCP server connected), use them to write and edit the workflow file. Never use the standard Write/Edit tools when the sky MCP server is connected. `skylence_read` returns a `¶path#TAG` header; pass it verbatim in `skylence_edit` patches.

MCP server rule: for any node in the generated workflow whose task requires an external tool (Cartographer graph queries, GitHub API, Slack, Linear, or any other MCP-backed capability), include an `mcp_servers` key in that node's §§ config block with the relevant server(s). A `claude` node that calls Cartographer must declare the cartographer MCP server; a node posting to Slack must declare the Slack MCP server. Omit `mcp_servers` only when no node needs an external tool.

Write the file — do not lint it yet.

Optional — add a `ui` key to one representative node (e.g. the first Claude prompt node) to demonstrate the dashboard card feature. When you include it, also create the companion markdown file at `{{dir}}/{{name}}/ui/<step>.en.md` (locale form) with YAML frontmatter:

```markdown
---
short_description: One-line summary shown on the node card.
long_description: Longer description shown when the card is expanded.
---
Brief markdown body describing what this step does, visible in the dashboard.
```

Wire it in the node config as `ui = "ui/<step>"` (extensionless, locale set). If the brief does not suggest any node that benefits from a card description, omit the `ui` key entirely — do not add it for its own sake.

Also add a workflow-level `ui = "ui/workflow"` key to the `⊕meta⊕` block (always include this), and create `{{dir}}/{{name}}/ui/workflow.en.md` with:

```markdown
---
short_description: One-line — what the workflow does.
long_description: The problem it solves and why it came to be.
changelog:
  - version: "1.0.0"
    date: "{{today}}"
    note: "Initial release."
---
Brief markdown body giving a human-readable overview of the workflow.
```

The `changelog` list supports `version` (required), `date` (optional, ISO 8601), and `note` (required). Include at least one entry.
∆∆

※lint※
Step 2 — lint & fix. Loop node (max 6 passes) that reads {{dir}}/{{name}}/workflow.sky,
runs sky lint, and fixes all errors. Edge: depends_on=["author"], trigger_rule=all_done.
Condition: loop.until.bash exits 0 (clean lint) or loop.max exhausted.
※※

§lint§
model = "sonnet"
depends_on = ["author"]
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
loop.until.bash = "sky lint \"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NAME/workflow.sky\""
loop.max = 6
§§

∆lint∆
Read {{dir}}/{{name}}/workflow.sky, then run `sky lint {{dir}}/{{name}}/workflow.sky` and read its output. Fix every reported error and warning in the file, using the sky-workflow-authoring skill's error-code table (SKY-WF-*) to map each code to its fix. Common ones: quote the RHS of `when`; add `chain_from` targets to `depends_on`; quote `$SKY_*` in bash; declare every env-var reference in the `secrets` array. SKY-WF-103 (warning): `ui` key points to a markdown file that does not exist (applies to both the workflow-level `ui` in `⊕meta⊕` and per-node `ui` keys); create the missing file(s) at the declared path(s), or remove the key. Keep the workflow body in English. Re-run lint after editing. This node loops until lint passes; make concrete fixes each pass. When clean, output the final lint result and the file path.

File editing rule: if `skylence_read` and `skylence_edit` MCP tools are available (sky MCP server connected), use them for all reads and edits of the workflow file. Never use the standard Read/Edit/Write tools when the sky MCP server is connected.
∆∆
